<br>
Firstly, I would like to lend my voice to the chorus that has commended LoM for their fairness. By allowing others a shot, they are certainly not trying to control the rotation for the rest of the server. That may be an unfortunate side effect to generosity, but with a rotation as large as the Sev rotation, one must expect delays and speed bumps. I am certain that in upcoming weeks, the sev rotation will be talked about in great length, ironically having to do with it's great length. <br>
<br>
For the moment, however, I would like to examine a few suggestions coming out of this discussion. <br>
<br>
First, it is a very bad idea to suggest an involuntary removal from a rotation, on several levels. <br>
<br>
The rotations on arguably &quot;easy&quot; mobs like Sev or Trak, which also are our most congested rotations, are long waits on mobs that have very little to interest most guilds that can kill them... *except* one piece that a guild either needs *many* of, *OR* that is a rarer drop and requires multiple kills. <br>
<br>
We, of the RTA, should *never* forget, that we are a convention, and a powerless one when it comes to *actual* in game actions. I believe SoY said it best when there was issues with their entry to the Statue rotation: (I'm paraphrasing here, but it's approximately right). <br>
<br>
'If you want us to kill another one in a week, rather than 2 months, that's fine by us'. <br>
<br>
If we remove guilds from a rotation, where there are obviously already capable of killing the mob, we cannot enforceably keep them from killing that mob over, and over, and over. Hell, we really can't stop that from happening now, aside from dropping flame bombs on those who would violate the rotations. <br>
<br>
At no time can the RTA say &quot;you are not allowed to kill mob X anymore&quot;. It is a public game, and as much as it would clear up the rotation, it would also undermine the authority of the RTA's, as people said a big 'fuck you' to the restrictions on them. <br>
<br>
I know, personally, as a guild on the sev rotation, if we were removed, it wouldn't keep us out of the Emerald Jungle. If anything, we'd be there more often, to force our reinstatement. <br>
<br>
I would ask any guild who no longer needs trak or sev to leave the rotation *but* I would also argue that guilds short of the AoW rotation would not be able to field a warrior that is as effective as possible, without their epic hate proc. I *believe* the BoC is the first obtainable hate proc that is not the epic. Perhaps that club from the plane of innovation will fit into that category, but the point is really moot at this point: people want, and will fight to get, their epics. <br>
<br>
In any event, removal, in an involuntary way, will lead to a FFA mob, not a less cluttered rotation. It may work in theory, but people will always be the variable, and when I say that we would still hit sev repeatedly if off the rotation, it speaks to the amount that others would as well. (Keeping in mind that I am the biggest pussy about confrontation on this server.)<br>
<br>
I would suggest that we adopt a rule that does not discourage fairness, but that also keeps a rotation moving along quickly: <br>
<br>
Guilds may only allow one guild to go ahead of them per turn around the rotation; after that, if they are beaten to, or allow another guild to go ahead of them, that guild is inserted AFTER them in the rotation, in effect, forcing a pass. <br>
<br>
Example:<br>
<br>
Clan Bashemded up for Dozekar: We pass to United Necros as a courtesy, they win and get into the rotation *behind* us. <br>
<br>
The next week, we're up for dozekar again, and we pass to let Fallen Shadows kill Doze. They dead him as well, but this time, they go into the rotation after Clan Bashemded, making sure that SoY will get a go, or an opportunity to pass at their discretion in at least a semi-timely fashion. <br>
<br>
I think this will create a higher level of competition to race to, and kill faster, the rare spawns that we have on rotation, while also allowing a guild to still be generous without major penalty. <br>
<br>
This may *sound* harsh for a moment, but really, lets examine what it comes down to here:<br>
<br>
From the moment they allow another guild to kill a rotation mob, the guild up for that mob has between 3 days and 7 days to plan to be ready for that mob to pop. If, given between 72 and 168 hours to prepare for a mob pop, a guild still either cannot bring sufficent numbers or has better things to do with those numbers, then they are holding up the rotation in one way or another, and should be moved over to continue the timely addition of phat lewt to our server. <br>
<br>
This obviously is not a retroactive suggestion, nor is it an official word on the subject, just one man's suggestion. But I think to foster a more goal-oriented playstyle, there should be at least *some* degree of urgency to getting to a mob, and I think this suggestion will create that, while not fostering the hate and rush of a FFA environment. <br>
<br>
As it is, it just creates a situation in which a guild *knows* they are going to get a mob within a set amount of time after they are &quot;due&quot;. <br>
<br>
But again, this is not a slight against any guild, but something that would allow a rotation to continue moving ahead with some speed. <br>
<br>
Thoughts?<br>
